<b>Warning</b>:  Supplied argument is not a valid MySQL result resource in <b>/usr/local/www/vhosts/decktech.net/htdocs/global/includes/com/buzzboard.php</b> on line <b>251</b><br>
<table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF">For john lolli: Deck Size discussion.  Last three 50+ player tournaments won by 72+ card decks</font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="bfont"> From: neal</font><BR><font class="bfont"><A HREF='/lotr/resources/buzz.php'>Back to Topics List</A></font><TABLE WIDTH=100% border="0" cellpadding="6"><tr><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="h2font"> Name</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="h2font"> Comment</td></tr><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Not to be argumentative Zaphod but really it is the same thing.<br>
<br>
Just like Magic, if you cant play the cards in your hand, your screwed. LOTR has an advantage of discarding a card to draw another, or using game text to get rid of unwanted cards, where Magic, you draw 1 card a turn unless you use a card to draw more cards, LOTR has it built in so you can come back from a hand flood in LOTR much easier than Magic.<br>
<br>
I remember the good old days, mox jet, ritual, ritual Juzam Djinn, strip mine your land, go. LOTR doesnt really have any of that and that is a good thing in my opinion. You dont lose on the first turn, or at least you never should. You dont lose in Magic first turn either but in reality, your opening hand can win or lose the game , where LOTR you have a chance to make it up through multiple card draws a turn.<br>
<br>
Ever look at your opening hand in Rings and see 7 minions? Opponent deploys a sword and says, I&#39;ll walk.<br>
<br>
Same as in Magic, draw seven cards, 6 creatures (or whatever) and 1 land and your opponent says, dark ritual, Ice Storm, you might as well get up and walk away.<br>
<br>
I saw a site 2 corruption Sunday that was comical since the guy bid 9 with no Sam and first turn twilight and resistance is unbearable. lol </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Zaphod</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Judge, You&#39;re correct, choke is really good against Uruks. What&#39;s your point?  That&#39;s totally different than being mana screwed.  If my hand is full of Uruks I can&#39;t play, than my opponents deck is working the way it&#39;s supposed to.  In fact, the only game I lost at NY territorials was to a moria choke deck that I built for a friend of mine.<br>
<br>
Bad Player, I know what I&#39;m talking about when it comes to Magic, so don&#39;t give me this "bad deckbuilder" crap. I&#39;ve won more than my share of MTG tournaments.  I wasn&#39;t just talking about mana screw, but just the fact that missing land drops, getting mana flooded, or getting all mana of one color (no matter how many painlands are in your deck) happens all the time.  All of those situations make it so that your deck isn&#39;t played to it&#39;s full extent, and somebody with a worse deck can still beat you if they draw a good ratio of mana to "business" spells.<br>
<br>
In lotr, the person with the better deck is going to win just about every time, because they can cycle through their deck without having to worry about how much mana they have.  Like I said, magic may have more chess like strategy decisions, but it a far inferior deck building game, IN MY OPINION. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Bad Player</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Continuing from my previous post...<br>
<br>
- Creating the balance between spells and resources is definitely the most difficult part of building a deck. Practically every sealed or draft deck is multi-color, and 90+% of the current Standard (type 2) decks are as well. (If you don&#39;t believe this, check out www.sideboard.com and check out the results from the US Nationals).<br>
You have to consider the cost of your spells, the types of mana required in your spells, and other things such as cheap creatures that produce mana, or cheap instants that draw you cards, etc. If your deck is slow and has many spells costing 4 or more, then you need to play more than just the typical 2-to-1 spell to land ratio. You also have to account for the colors of mana your deck requires, and how many of your spells require two of a certain color of mana.<br>
<br>
- There are multiple schools of thought for deckbuilding. MTG decks can be pro-active ("aggro"), reactive ("control"), or a blend of the two ("aggro-control"). With LOTR, every deck is basically the same in this train of thought (aggro-control, because of the split between FP and shadow). Your shadow is there for a combination of drawing into your fellowship cards and slowing your opponent down. Your shadow side should be filled with "threats", while every fellowship should have the "answers." I&#39;ll take a quote from a pro MTG player (I can&#39;t remember the name): "There are no wrong threats, only wrong answers."<br>
If you draw enough answers to handle your opponent&#39;s Shadow, then your fellowship will succeed. If you don&#39;t draw the right answers, or your opponents draw a sufficient number of threats, then your fellowship falls and you lose. This makes basically every LOTR game the same.<br>
With MTG, decks are much more interesting, where you can have varying strategies playing against each other. <br>
 </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>neal</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">I agree with Charlie.  Like maybe one of 10-15 games do you get mana screwed enough to make a difference, if you build a good deck.  I always played more than the "rule of 33%".  It does happen though, and there&#39;s nothing you can do, usually. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Bad Player</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">I think this Zaphod kid really wasn&#39;t that great of a MTG deckbuilder if he keeps complaining about mana-screw.<br>
 I&#39;m sorry, but a deck with a solid mana base for it&#39;s spells, combined with thorough shuffling between games, should result in very few times where you don&#39;t draw land. Also, you can mulligan your opening hand no matter what, shuffle your hand back, and draw one less new card. If you don&#39;t draw land, you can give yourself more chances to draw lands. If you get mana screwed more than 10% of the time, you should certainly blame the deck and not your luck.<br>
<br>
As for LOTR, well, if you don&#39;t draw enough fellowship cards (via choke or just bad luck), then you will likely lose.<br>
<br>
And as for MTG deckbuilding, since Zaphod don&#39;t seem to be that great of a deckbuilder, I&#39;ll key everyone who cares in on a few things:<br>
-Decks do draw cards. Games in both constructed and sealed rarely end after just a couple of turns. Between draw steps and cards that have drawing effects, you&#39;ll eventually see that card you&#39;re playing 1 or 2 of that can break a stalemate or just flat out win you the game in a given situation. This makes deck construction a little more fun and challenging.<br>
<br>
More to come in a couple of mins. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Uh, Zaphod....you might want to consider playing your Uraks against a choke deck and watch them clog the crap out of your hand and see how well the deck works.<br>
<br>
