deck usually decks itself in close games, and comes close (10 cards or less) in most games. That means that I get to see most of my fellowship cards.. and that I have a good chance of drawing key cards.<br>
<br>
Just a ramble, more to come later probably. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Gwemegil and They are Coming= good cycling. It only helps to get the cards out of your hand by the way. It didn&#39;t help that you got unlucky and drew a bunch of stuff that you already had on the table so it is a double edged sword so to speak. If all your cards are playable then you should only have to pitch cards when you are going for the kill with minions or making that dreaded 7-9 final move. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>faramir</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Hmm, lemme chime in here.  Your deck should be small enough so that in a close game where you go through a lot of cards you see every card.  Ideally you would see every card in your deck, every game, but that&#39;s just not gonna happen, some games are quick races and others are long drawn out struggles.  It&#39;s great to say that your deck has an answer for everything, but this doesn&#39;t help you if you never see that answer cause your deck is too big.  You&#39;d be better off not having the answer for everything, and instead having the answer for the things you expect to see.  Don&#39;t get me wrong, I like big decks, but if I&#39;m gonna play a big deck I&#39;m gonna play cards that help me see the whole thing (as needed).  I have no problems playing an 70 card Uruk deck w/ 3 Gwemegils and ditching my entire hand to it at a critical point in the game.  Some decks thrive on seeing particular cards, others benefit from the versatility of seeing a lot of cards, both are viable strategies. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">As stated before, building a deck to win is pretty simple. You can put all those tasty weapons and companions in your deck all day long. If you draw them, you ought to do well. If you don&#39;t you are likely doomed.<br>
<br>
A long close tight game usually means that a) both players drew all the good stuff or b) both players had bad draws.<br>
<br>
A total slaughter or walk through means the exact opposite. 1 player= good draw and 1 bad draw.<br>
<br>
It aint that hard to figure out people. If you build a 74 card deck and every card is useful when you draw it, that seems reasonable to me. If it is a bunch of junk that you will hold for 2 or 3 sites like drawing 2 Servants in your opening hand then that is bad luck. Its not necessarily bad construction, it means you better get that out of your hand quick. Gondors Vengeance is one of the worst cards in the game if you draw it opening hand or if you draw it at site 8!!!<br>
<br>
If your deck is designed to draw a card and play it immediately, you will never fear the dreaded hand clog and you wont sit on cards at all.<br>
<br>
If you insist on using pump cards and Servants and multiple weapons and goofy cards that are situational then you will get hand clog and that can lose games for people unless you draw it exactly when its needed.<br>
<br>
The bigger decks on paper look terrible but they can be just as useful and competetive with good draws, good matchups, and a good player using it, the same as a smaller deck can. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>neal</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Trevor was in the final and charlie and vincent vega just missed it.  They&#39;ve shown you can win with small decks.  So which has the advantage, that&#39;s what i&#39;m trying to sort out. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Yoda Killa</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">I would have to agree with Kim here, as long as the cards in your deck are all necessary and useful, it can be made bigger. <br>
<br>
And as for "Team Atlanta", look how well your belief in small size decks did you at your own DPC(not withstanding Trevor&#39;s deck, but don&#39;t get me started on that :P).  </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Kessling</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Personally and almost all of the Atlanta players believe that a smaller deck is better. Vincent Vega, myself, and Trevor Bradley all want to have drawn our entire deck at site nine. Normally we play 60-62 in any culture besides moria for shadow and 64 for moria. <br><br>We also somehow manage to build versatile fellowships with support cards and many companions while sticking to around 60 cards. The truth is that this game is all reliant on deck construction and the luck of your draw. Playing less cards allows for you to have a better chance of drawing what you will need and to play less of every card. I believe that playing more than 70 cards with any shadow culture is too many unless your deck is capable of running through cards at lightning speed. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Arwen Even*</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Hmmmm... as a player of one of said decks, I should probably venture an opinion...  I won the PA territorial with an 80-card deck, Nazgul of all things.  After the tournament I did what I always do, go through it and see what proved useful and what did not to cut out the dead wood.  And the thing is, I didn&#39;t find any.<br>
<br>
Why is the deck that big?  Because I refuse to play with a fellowship that isn&#39;t well-rounded enough to stand up to whatever comes its way.  Every single fellowship card proved vital in one game or another, be it something as seemingly useless as a Celeborn out with no other elven allies (used him for Secret Sentinels and killed him at 6).  <br>
<br>
The Shadow half is 40 cards just to match it.  Unlike other cultures, just 1 or 2 Nazgul minions played properly can be very deadly.  So if I don&#39;t have a glutted shadow hand, it&#39;s no big deal.  Do I play numerous support cards?  Yes, because in today&#39;s playing environment (at least around here) they&#39;re needed to make any kind of a dent in super fellowship.  What&#39;s the point of loading up the deck with minions that get cut down while you blink?  I&#39;d rather risk doing significant damage half the time over no damage all the time.  Nazgul aren&#39;t really prone to overwhelming with numbers...<br>
<br>
Is luck part of it?  Of course.  Luck is a part of life.  But there are certainly ways that you can tip the odds in your favor.  I DIDN&#39;T go first in every game, I drew a LOT of crappy opening hands, and there were times I could NOT catch a break.  There were also times I did.<br>
<br>
My deck is 80 cards, but it&#39;s 80 USEFUL cards.  What should I take out?  I&#39;ve been told to ditch the eleven allies and the mirror, they add too many cards... but let&#39;s see, there was that one game when the mirror yanked the minion that killed me at site 9, and the cave troll, and the spies, and when Celeborn died at 6 to save one of my companions, and when Orophin made the Troop&#39;s vitality low enough for him to get PATHSed...<br>
<br>
Or I could take out the Gondor&#39;s Vengeances, they can&#39;t be used all the time... but wait, they let me double move to 9 all those times...  Or wait, COMPANIONS, I don&#39;t need those, right?  They take up WAY too much room...<br>
<br>
Is 80 cards a lot?  Yes.  But I DO have ways to rip through it.  Gwemegil works well.  And I also have two TACs and two Goblin Scrabblers just for that purpose.  (Well, that and to get rid of Last Alliances and Tale of Gil-galads and what not).  Winning is a combination of luck, playing skill, and deckbuilding ability, right?  Nobody is lucky enough to win at that level on luck alone.  Let me guess, the same deck (let alone the same size deck) winning 2 different DPC&#39;s is luck too?   </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Arwenslave</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">I guess I better ring in on this one, since it was (somewhat) a shot at me :)<br>
<br>
True, I am huge believer in the under 70 card deck concept. I have built Moria swarm deck up to 90 cards, but I don&#39;t think any other deck type deserve 70 or more cards and I am sticking to that belief.<br>
<br>
Here is my reasoning:<br>
<br>
1) Moria and TAC:<br>
<br>
Moria allows you to use TAC to ditch cards that are not useful at the moment, and rewards you with cards you can use immediately. Other cultures don&#39;t have this, and if you water down another culture with TAC and let&#39;s say runners, the deck isn&#39;t as strong. Obviously as we all know this allows you to get cards out of your hand that is clogging it up. And please don&#39;t tell me, well, don&#39;t put cards in that clog your hand. I mean cards that are not useful at the moment, like when your opponent is double moving, and you have 6 fellowship cards left in your hand.<br>
<br>
2) The mirror issue and <br>
shadow side:<br>
<br>
Right now, the mirror is so strong, that playing numerous shadow support cards instead of actual minions, can really hurt you. Support cards are great, like conditions or events, but if the minions are taken out of your hand, the support cards are useless. Now, the more cards you play, let&#39;s say 36 instead of 32, those 4 extra cards usually are some type of support card. This lowers the percentage chance you have of drawing a minion shadow card instead of a support shadow card. Each culture only has a limited number of "good" minion cards. And statistically, I want to draw the good minions, not just average minions. If each culture had more good minions, then I could justify playing more cards.<br>
<br>
3) Fellowship side:<br>
<br>
The last time I checked, no one was winning with all men, or all hobbits, or all dwarves. Good decks mix cultures. Also, the last time I checked, no one was able to start all the characters they were going to play at the start of the game. This being said, it will always be important to find the characters you need, allies included, and the support cards that go with them. How useful is galadriel without the mirror. How useful is sleep without gandalf. I don&#39;t have to explain statistics to make my point here. Every card you play is important in your deck, otherwise it wouldn&#39;t be in there. And the smaller the deck, the fewer copies of a card you have to play, and the better the chance of seeing the card early. I don&#39;t like having to play multiples. The first gwemegil I pull is useful, the second is useless (unless cantea knocks it away of course).<br>
<br>
4) Useful/Less specific cards:<br>
<br>
I couldn&#39;t agree more with this notion. I always try to put versatile cards in. Start Gandalf, play servants. Play Arwen, Boromir and Aragorn, use ranger pumpers, brands, ARV. But I can also play fewer version of these cards, and thin out the deck, and better my chances of seeing the cards when I need them.<br>
<br>
All of this being said, I somehow went 4-4 at my first major event, so what the hell do I know? Hopefully after this weekend at NJ territorials, I will be able to speak with some respect about what is good and what isn&#39;t. If I have another bad day, then maybe everyone should try 150 card decks. :) </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Asterisk</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Play a good card, reconcile, draw a good card. Play a good card and a decent card, reconcile, draw a good card and a decent card.<br>
<br>
Playing more cards gives you more resources and potentially more "answers" to your opponent. The more cards you play, the more cards you need, or you run out of resources and exhaust your "answers". True, you have less in the beginning, and throughput is relative, so while you go through your deck, you don&#39;t get as many cards, but consider this:<br>
<br>
1) how hard is the move from 1-3?<br>
2) so far in this game, quantity does fare slightly better than quality<br>
3) going through close to 20-25 cards in 1 fellowship, 1 shadow, and the starting 8, how hard is it to set up survival through moria?<br>
4) after going through half your deck in moria, how hard is it to set up some more?<br>
<br>
You get cards you need through fast throughput and a conequence of this is a big deck. A deck that goes through 60 cards is simply not going to have enough to consistently damage the opponent/double move as much as one with inexhaustible resources. Of course, luck is still a tremendous factor in this game, so it is hard to tell as of now, but there are reasons that big decks are winning. No matter how big luck is, i see 24 games in front of me, a great majority of which were won by big decks. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Blind luck and coincidence is my first thought.<br>
<br>
The decks might be good on paper but yes, conventional wisdom and mathematics tell us that looking for a certain card in a deck is harder with a bigger deck right?<br>
<br>
Well, if you have a deck that doesnt rely on a certain card to get pulled and you play whatever you draw and it helps you then it shouldnt matter if your deck is 60 cards or 160 right?<br>
<br>
Hogwash. What it comes down to is matchups, who goes first, and getting even a reasonable draw after that.<br>
<br>
If your matched against some scrub with no idea what is going on, even a marginal deck should prevail. Good player against good player, ala Bradley versus Lewis was a good matchup with Lewis having the "edge" using Uraks against unprotected companions so it was a good matchup of 2 good decks, 2 good players, but 1 dck having an obvious advantage over the other.<br>
<br>
What does this solve? Nothing!!! This game is very much about luck, double moving when you can, and good draw versus bad draw.<br>
<br>
Oh you have no minions? I think Ill move again. Its rather retarded. Thats why Sting, Glamdring, and the mirror are so darn powerful.<br>
<br>
Site 3, I Sting you. Cool no minions. I&#39;ll double move almost every time. Oh you have 3 minions, Ill use the mirror. Grab 2 with some luck and double move fearing nothing. Miss them both and then reevaluate it after battling. Its pretty easy.<br>
<br>
Once you have it figured out, this game is easy. It all comes down to luck after that. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Max of Tat</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">They heard about my dwarf discard deck and fear it? (=<br>
<br>
<br>
In actuality, I think it&#39;s because of the larger fellowships, and versitility (not the card). Every turn, throw all you&#39;ve got, and get some more for next turn.<br>
<br>
At major tournaments like the DPC and Opens, players have to be able to expect and handle anything that comes their way. On both sides of the deck. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Lt. Cabbage</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">It doesn&#39;t suprise me that much.  It seems that the top decks are built to be capable of dealing with many situations and this tends to need a big deck.  But I think it depends on your card pool.  If, like me, you only have one or two of the decent mains then I think you&#39;re better off keeping the deck size down, to increase the chance of drawing the good cards.  Unless you&#39;re playing Moria that is as that definitely needs a deck size off 70 cards plus. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>neal</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Seems the conventional wisdom, esp early on, is that you should keep your decks as close to 60 cards as possible.  There are many good arguments and reasonings for this, such as the bigger the deck, the less chance you have of drawing the cards you need.<br>
<br>
However, for hundreds of years it was accepted that a heavier object would fall faster than a smaller object.  Why, none other than Aristotle himself had logically proven that the heavier object must fall faster!<br>
<br>
One problem: Aristotle was a lazy psuedo intellectual who never bothered to test anything, he just ran his mouth.  Yeah, sounds like some DT members, doesn&#39;t it?  Turns out when people actually tested his theory, he was dead wrong.  Obviously, we all know now, objects fall at the same speed with = air resistances.<br>
<br>
So let&#39;s trash the conventional wisdom a bit with results<br>
<br>
DPC Vegas - 54 people - won by a 72 card deck<br>
DPC Atlanta - 64 people largest ever, won by a 72 card deck<br>
PA Territorial - 50 people - won by an 80 card deck<br>
<br>
Can anyone account for this? </TD></TR><TR><TD colspan='2'><font class="bfont"><A HREF='/lotr/resources/buzz.php'>Back to Topics List</A></font></TD></TD></TABLE><p><font class="bfont"><b>You must be a member to add topics to this list.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
